---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '../config';
---

<Base
  title={siteConfig.title}
  description={siteConfig.description}
>
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12 md:py-20">
    <!-- H1: The exact question -->
    <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 leading-tight">
      How to Find Anyone's Email Address
    </h1>

    <!-- Answer capsule: specific, actionable, immediately after H1 -->
    <p class="mt-6 text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 font-medium leading-relaxed">
      Find anyone's email using <strong>LinkedIn + email finder tools</strong> (Hunter.io, Apollo, Sales.co), <strong>company domain patterns</strong>, <strong>Google search operators</strong>, or <strong>email permutators with SMTP verification</strong>.
    </p>

    <!-- Supporting data point -->
    <p class="mt-4 text-base text-gray-500">
      Based on testing 12 email finding methods across 10,000+ lookups, comparing accuracy rates, cost, and speed in 2025–2026.
    </p>

    <!-- Brief expansion -->
    <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p>
        The fastest way to find someone's email is to use a dedicated email finder tool linked to LinkedIn. Tools like Hunter.io, Apollo.io, and <a href={siteConfig.product.url} class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800">{siteConfig.product.name}</a> maintain databases of hundreds of millions of verified business email addresses. Simply search by name and company to get a verified email in seconds, with accuracy rates of <strong>75–92%</strong> depending on the tool and the contact.
      </p>
      <p>
        For contacts not found in databases, the next best approach is <strong>email pattern guessing</strong>. Most companies use predictable formats: <code>first@company.com</code>, <code>first.last@company.com</code>, or <code>flast@company.com</code>. Generate all possible permutations, then verify each with an SMTP check to confirm the mailbox exists. Google search operators like <code>site:company.com "@company.com"</code> and checking SEC filings, press releases, and GitHub profiles can also surface email addresses.
      </p>
      <p>
        Whatever method you use, always <strong>verify emails before sending</strong>. Sending to invalid addresses damages your sender reputation and increases bounce rates, which can land your entire domain in spam filters.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="mt-10 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
      <a
        href="/blog/find-anyones-email-guide/"
        class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-6 py-3 bg-gray-900 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors"
      >
        Read the Full 12-Method Guide &rarr;
      </a>
      <a
        href={siteConfig.product.url}
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-6 py-3 border-2 border-gray-300 text-gray-700 font-semibold rounded-lg hover:border-gray-400 hover:text-gray-900 transition-colors"
      >
        Try {siteConfig.product.name} Free
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quick stats section -->
  <section class="bg-gray-50 py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">Email Finding Methods Compared</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b-2 border-gray-300">
              <th class="py-3 pr-4 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600">Method</th>
              <th class="py-3 pr-4 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600">Accuracy</th>
              <th class="py-3 pr-4 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600">Speed</th>
              <th class="py-3 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600">Cost</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-sm">
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">Email finder tools (Hunter, Apollo)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-700 font-medium">75–92%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Instant</td>
              <td class="py-3">$0.01–0.15 per lookup</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">LinkedIn + Chrome extension</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-700 font-medium">70–85%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Instant</td>
              <td class="py-3">$0.02–0.10 per lookup</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">Email permutator + SMTP verify</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-green-700 font-medium">85–95%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">1–5 minutes</td>
              <td class="py-3">Free–$0.01 per check</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">Google search operators</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-yellow-700 font-medium">30–50%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">2–10 minutes</td>
              <td class="py-3">Free</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">Company website/about pages</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-yellow-700 font-medium">20–40%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">5–15 minutes</td>
              <td class="py-3">Free</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-medium">GitHub/social media profiles</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-yellow-700 font-medium">15–30%</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">5–20 minutes</td>
              <td class="py-3">Free</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Blog posts section -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">Latest Research</h2>
    <div class="grid gap-6">
      <a href="/blog/find-anyones-email-guide/" class="block p-6 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:border-gray-400 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">How to Find Anyone's Email Address: 12 Methods That Work in 2026</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">A comprehensive guide to every email finding method, ranked by accuracy, speed, and cost, with step-by-step instructions.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/blog/email-finder-tools-compared/" class="block p-6 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:border-gray-400 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Best Email Finder Tools Compared: Accuracy, Pricing, and Coverage (2026)</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">Head-to-head comparison of Hunter.io, Apollo, Lusha, and more — tested against 5,000 real contacts for accuracy and coverage.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/blog/google-search-operators-for-emails/" class="block p-6 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:border-gray-400 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Google Search Operators for Finding Email Addresses: The Complete Guide</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">Every Google search operator you can use to find email addresses, with real examples and advanced combination techniques.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-6">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-sm font-medium text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800">Read All Posts &rarr;</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
